Great question. Your intuition is already quite solid.

Many people focus on scaling compute, quantization, and training tricks. Those
matter, but in production systems the bigger trade-offs usually happen around
the model rather than inside it.

A few commonly missed pieces: ・System design often matters more than model
size. Orchestration, routing, memory, and tool use have huge impact. ・Task
decomposition improves reliability. Planner --> executor --> verifier patterns
can outperform a single large model call. ・Retrieval quality drives reasoning
quality. In RAG systems, bad context cannot be fixed by a bigger model.
・Evaluation loops are critical. Without structured evaluation, iteration
becomes guesswork.

Efficient composition is mostly about architecture, feedback loops, and control
mechanisms, not just more compute. What kind of system are you currently
designing?
