Great question. The main trade-offs around the model usually fall into three
areas. On the hardwre side, GPU memory limits context size and batching.
Latency requirements limit how many model calls you can chain. Throughput and
cost constraints often push you toward smaller models with smarter routing
instead of on large model.

On the data side, retrieval precision versus recall is critical. More context
increases coverage but also noise. You also need to balance index size,
freshness and latency. Planning in LLM system is usually implemented as
structured decomposition. The model generates a plan in text. The system parses
it into steps and executes them sequentially. Sometimes another model verifies
the result. It is less like control-theory extrapolation and more like
probabilistic reasoning wrapped in deterministic scaffolding.

