Makes sense.
You are essentially asking how to plan the development of LLM system before committing to large models and heavy iteration.
In practice, the process usually starts with defining evaluation first.
You define concrete tasks, success metrics and filure modes.
Then you prototype with existing strong model to establish a performance ceiling.
After that you progressively constrain the system.
You reduce model size, narrow context or introduce structure and measure the drop in quality versus gains in cost and latency.

Sharinking the necessary LLM is ofen possible if you add structure around it .
Task decomposition, retrieval grounding, tool use and constrained outputs can allow smaller models to perform well.
In many production systems, a smaller model plus good scaffolding outperforms a large model used naively.

The usefulness of shringking depens on your constraints.
If cost, latency or deployment on limited hardware matters it is very valuable.
If the task is highly open-ended reaoning, the gains may be limited.

